<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="62" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1485,1623]" pageId="13" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,348,1485,1511]" pageId="13" pageNumber="62">Comments.</emphasis>
Similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[493,639,1486,1511]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Chrysotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis box="[493,639,1486,1511]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="62">C. robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished from it as noted above. The original description of 
<bibRefCitation author="Robinson" box="[324,526,1523,1549]" pageId="13" pageNumber="64" refString="Robinson, H. (1975) Bredin-Archibold-Smithsonian biological survey of Dominica, the family Dolichopodidae with some related Antillean and Panamanian species (Diptera). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 185, 1 - 141." type="journal article" year="1975">
Robinson (
<number box="[455,517,1523,1549]" pageId="13" pageNumber="62" value="1975.0">1975</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
does not mention the asymmetrical rows of dc, neither the presence of four postpronotal setae in the 
<typeStatus box="[453,557,1560,1586]" pageId="13" pageNumber="62">holotype</typeStatus>
(not visible in the 
<typeStatus box="[786,895,1560,1586]" pageId="13" pageNumber="62">paratype</typeStatus>
). This may be teratogenic, so examination of more material may resolve this question.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
